==Game notes== ===Rice=== {{AFB game box start |Visitor= Rice |V1= 0 |V2= 3 |V3= 14 |V4= 7 |Host= '''UAB''' |H1= 7 |H2= 20 |H3= 14 |H4= 3 |Location= [[Legion Field]], [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Alabama]] |StartTime= 3:07 p.m. |TimeZone= Central |ElapsedTime= 3:05 |Attendance= 14,316 |Weather= 77Â°F, Cloudy, humid |Referee= Bill Athan |TVAnnouncers= |TVStation= CSS}} {{AFB game box end}}
{{See also|2009 Rice Owls football team}} To open the 2009 season, UAB [[quarterback]] [[Joe Webb]] would have a record setting day in leading the Blazers to this 44-24 victory over the Owls. For the game, Webb would set both a school and [[Conference USA]] record for rushing yards by a quarterback in a single game with 194.<ref name="2009Rice">{{cite web |url=http://uabsports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090509aaa.html |title=UAB Opens Season With 44-24 Win Over Rice |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham Sports Information |accessdate=2009-09-26|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kAurGYoB|archivedate=2009-09-30|deadurl=no}}</ref> For the game, Webb would also complete 12 of 15 passes for another 221 yards and a pair of touchdowns in gaining 415 yards of total offense on the afternoon.<ref name="2009Rice"/> For his efforts, Webb was named Conference USA Offensive Player of the Week.<ref name="September 7, 2009">{{cite news | last =Irvine | first =Steve | title =Joe Webb earns a pair of honors | work =The Birmingham News | date =September 7, 2009}}</ref>
===SMU=== {{AFB game box start |Visitor= '''SMU''' |V1= 14 |V2= 14 |V3= 0 |V4= 7 |Host= UAB |H1= 0 |H2= 7 |H3= 20 |H4= 6 |Location= Legion Field, Birmingham, Alabama |StartTime= 3:00 p.m. |TimeZone= Central |ElapsedTime= 3:27 |Attendance= 18,082 |Weather= 84Â°F, Partly sunny, muggy |Referee= Claur Gausman }} {{AFB game box end}}
{{See also|2009 SMU Mustangs football team}} Following an opening week win, the Blazers would fall by a final score of 33-35 to the Mustangs of SMU. After falling behind by a score of 28-7 at the half, the Blazers would rally to within a point of SMU by the end of the third quarter.<ref name="2009SMU">{{cite web |url=http://uabsports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2009-2010/uabfb02.html |title=SMU vs UAB (Sept 12, 2009) |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham Sports Information |accessdate=2009-09-26}}</ref> The Blazers would fall late in the fourth following a failed [[two-point conversion]] that would have tied the game at 35 with 00:13 remaining in the game. For the game Webb would rush for 97 yards and a single touchdown in addition to throwing for 226 yards and a pair of touchdowns.<ref name="2009SMU"/>
===Troy=== {{AFB game box start |Visitor= UAB |V1= 0 |V2= 0 |V3= 6 |V4= 8 |Host= '''Troy''' |H1= 3 |H2= 7 |H3= 14 |H4= 3 |Location= [[Movie Gallery Stadium]], [[Troy, Alabama|Troy]], [[Alabama]] |StartTime= 2:36 p.m. |TimeZone= Central |ElapsedTime= 3:20 |Attendance= 21,182 |Weather= 84Â°F, Overcast |Referee= Jeff Roberson }} {{AFB game box end}}
{{See also|2009 Troy Trojans football team}} For the second week in a row, the Blazers would fall, and this time it was by a final score of 14-27 on the road to the Trojans of Troy. For the game, UAB only scored on a pair of Josh Zahn [[Field goal (football)|field goal]]s and a single, 17-yard Joe Webb touchdown pass in the fourth.<ref name="2009Troy">{{cite web |url=http://uabsports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2009-2010/uabfb03.html |title=UAB vs Troy (Sept 19, 2009) |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham Sports Information |accessdate=2009-09-26}}</ref>
===Texas A&M=== {{AFB game box start |Visitor= UAB |V1= 3 |V2= 3 |V3= 6 |V4= 7 |Host= '''Texas A&M''' |H1= 7 |H2= 21 |H3= 14 |H4= 14 |Location= [[Kyle Field]], [[College Station, Texas|College Station]], [[Texas]] |StartTime= 6:05 p.m. |TimeZone= Central |ElapsedTime= 3:05 |Attendance= 74,656 |Weather= 87Â°F, Fair |Referee= C. Castleberry }} {{AFB game box end}}
{{See also|2009 Texas A&M Aggies football team}} Traveling to College Station to face the Aggies in the evening, the Blazers would fall by a final score of 56-19. For the game, UAB scored on a pair of Josh Zahn [[Field goal (football)|field goal]]s, a 10-yard Joe Webb touchdown run in the third and on a 60-yard David Isabelle run in the fourth.<ref name="2009Texas">{{cite web |url=http://uabsports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090509aaa.html |title=UAB vs Texas A&M (Sept 26, 2009) |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham Sports Information |accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref>
===Southern Miss=== {{AFB game box start |Visitor= Southern Miss |V1= 0 |V2= 10 |V3= 0 |V4= 7 |Host= '''UAB''' |H1= 10 |H2= 0 |H3= 7 |H4= 13 |Location= Legion Field, Birmingham, Alabama |StartTime= 7:04 p.m. |TimeZone= Central |ElapsedTime= 3:07 |Attendance= 26,871 |Weather= 72Â°F, Clear |Referee= R.G. Detillier }} {{AFB game box end}}
{{See also|2009 Southern Miss Golden Eagles football team}} Following three consecutive losses in addition to coming off a short week, the Blazers would defeat Southern Miss for the first time in school history on a Thursday night by a final score of 30-17. UAB would open the scoring with a 27 yard Josh Zahn field goal and a 31-yard Joe Webb touchdown run in the first, only to have the Golden Eagles score 10 in the second to tie the game at the half.<ref name="2009SouthernMiss">{{cite web |url=http://www.webcitation.org/5kAurGYoB |title=Southern Miss vs UAB (Oct 1, 2009) |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham Sports Information |accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref> In the third, Webb would hit Anderson for a 21-yard touchdown in the third to take a 17-10 lead into the fourth.<ref name="2009SouthernMiss"/> Zahn would hit a pair of field goals (51 & 32 yards) and Hiram Atwater would seal the game late following a 40-yard interception return for a touchdown.<ref name="2009SouthernMiss"/>
